 **Example:**

 We have 50 recipe variable names. We want to create a table which shows 10 recipe variable names at the same time.
 We define a string array ``strArr: ARRAY[0..9] OF STRING;``
 Corresponding to the ``iStartIndex`` we can get the recipe variable names from a specific area.

 	- ``StartIndex`` := 0; The variable names 0..9 are returned.
 	- ``iStartIndex`` := 20; The variable names 20..29 are returned.

 In this example:

 	- ``iSize`` := 10;
 :return: Possible last error values:

		- |ERR_RECIPE_DEFINITION_NOT_FOUND|
		- |ERR_RECIPE_NOT_FOUND|
		- |ERR_NO_RECIPE_MANAGER_SET|
		- |ERR_OK|

 See :ref:`ReturnValues` for a description of all possible errors.]]></Comment><ReturnType>DWORD</ReturnType><ReturnBitSize>32</ReturnBitSize><Parameter><Name>RecipeDefinitionName</Name><Comment><![CDATA[	Name of the recipe definition ]]></Comment><Type>STRING(80)</Type><BitSize>648</BitSize></Parameter><Parameter><Name>RecipeName</Name><Comment><![CDATA[ Name of the recipe ]]></Comment><Type>STRING(80)</Type><BitSize>648</BitSize></Parameter><Parameter><Name>pStrings</Name><Comment><![CDATA[ The strings where the recipe values should be stored ]]></Comment><Type>STRING(80)</Type><ArrayInfo PointerTo="1"><LBound>0</LBound><Elements>1</Elements></ArrayInfo><BitSize>64</BitSize></Parameter><Parameter><Name>iSize</Name><Comment><![CDATA[ Size of the string array. ]]></Comment><Type>INT</Type><BitSize>16</BitSize></Parameter><Parameter><Name>iStartIndex</Name><Comment><![CDATA[ Start index. Can be used for a scrolling function (See example)]]></Comment><Type>INT</Type><BitSize>16</BitSize></Parameter></Method><Method><Name>ReadRecipe</Name><Comment><![CDATA[ Reads the current PLC values into the recipe

 :return: Possible last error values:

		- |ERR_RECIPE_DEFINITION_NOT_FOUND|
		- |ERR_RECIPE_NOT_FOUND|
		- |ERR_NO_RECIPE_MANAGER_SET|
		- |ERR_OK|
		- DataServer Errors from 16#2000 to 16#20FF, 
		- DataSourceDriver Errors from 16#2100 to 16#21FF

 DataServer and DataSourceDriver errors can occur if a DataServer and DataSource is configured beneth your current application (CODESYS HMI) and the command
 is called from the visualization.

 See :ref:`ReturnValues` for a description of all possible errors.]]></Comment><ReturnType>DWORD</ReturnType><ReturnBitSize>32</ReturnBitSize><Parameter><Name>RecipeDefinitionName</Name><Comment><![CDATA[	Name of the recipe definition ]]></Comment><Type>STRING(80)</Type><BitSize>648</BitSize></Parameter><Parameter><Name>RecipeName</Name><Comment><![CDATA[ Name of the recipe ]]></Comment><Type>STRING(80)</Type><BitSize>648</BitSize></Parameter><Local><Name>recSel</Name><Type Namespace="Recipe_Management">IRecipeSelection</Type><BitSize>64</BitSize></Local></Method><Method><Name>CreateRecipe</Name><Comment><![CDATA[ Creates a new recipe in the given recipe definition

 The method reads the current PLC values to the new recipe and saves them as a recipe file with the default name. 
 The default name is ``<recipe>.<recipe definition>.<recipe extension>``. At the end the new recipe would be stored in the default file.

 :return: Possible last error values:

		- |ERR_RECIPE_DEFINITION_NOT_FOUND|
		- |ERR_RECIPE_ALREADY_EXIST|
		- |ERR_RECIPE_NOMEMORY|
		- |ERR_NO_RECIPE_MANAGER_SET|
		- |ERR_OK|

