 Corresponding to the ``iStartIndex`` we can get the recipe names from a specific area.

 	- ``StartIndex`` := 0; The names 0..9 are returned.
 	- ``iStartIndex`` := 20; The names 20..29 are returned.

 In this example:

 	- ``iSize`` := 10;
 :return: Possible last error values:

		- |ERR_RECIPE_DEFINITION_NOT_FOUND|
		- |ERR_NO_RECIPE_MANAGER_SET|
		- |ERR_OK|

 See :ref:`ReturnValues` for a description of all possible errors.]]></Comment><ReturnType>DWORD</ReturnType><ReturnBitSize>32</ReturnBitSize><Parameter><Name>RecipeDefinitionName</Name><Comment><![CDATA[	Name of the recipe definition ]]></Comment><Type>STRING(80)</Type><BitSize>648</BitSize></Parameter><Parameter><Name>pStrings</Name><Comment><![CDATA[ The strings were the recipe values should be stored ]]></Comment><Type>STRING(80)</Type><ArrayInfo PointerTo="1"><LBound>0</LBound><Elements>1</Elements></ArrayInfo><BitSize>64</BitSize></Parameter><Parameter><Name>iSize</Name><Comment><![CDATA[ Size of the string array ]]></Comment><Type>INT</Type><BitSize>16</BitSize></Parameter><Parameter><Name>iStartIndex</Name><Comment><![CDATA[ Start index. Can be used for a scrolling function (see example)]]></Comment><Type>INT</Type><BitSize>16</BitSize></Parameter></Method><Method><Name>LoadRecipe</Name><Comment><![CDATA[ Loads a recipe from the standard recipe file

